New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> offer a perspective specifically in relation to Question 2:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“What are the factors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> that can influence police mis-recording of crime?”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My answer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">draws upon</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on academic research into UK police performance management </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that I am currently conducting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as part of my PhD studies at Warwic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">k Business School, as well as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">my professional experience as a serving</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> police</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> officer of 18 years. I </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wish to clarify however, that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vidence is presented</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on my own behalf, rather</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> than on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> behalf of my force, West Midlands Police.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My aim is to provide an insight into the root causes of police mis-recording of crime, to enable greater understand</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the factors responsible</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and to e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ncourage debate about how</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> future reoccurrences can be prevented.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction and Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This paper will examine the factors that influence police mis-recording of crime, addressing the following themes in sequence:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Background to current day police </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">performance management conventions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Summary of the main characteristics of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK police performance management.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The practice of using binary comparisons and how it can lead to behavioural dysfunction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">How the use of league tables can inadvertently cause unint</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ended consequences.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Numerical targets and how they act as a catalyst for gaming and unethical behaviour.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A discussion on the nature of potential responses to the problem of mis-recording.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Conclusion and a proposed direction for the future.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Context</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2. In or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">der to appreciate the impact of current day police performance practices and resultant behaviour, it is necessary to understand the evolution and recent history of UK police performance management; what follows is a brief summary. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The roots of modern d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ay police performance management in the UK can be traced to the early 1980s, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the drive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to demonstrate efficiency, economy and effectiveness. This heralded the beginning of a paradigmatic shift towards managerialism across the UK police service, which c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ame into being as part of wider public service reforms of the era, known as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">New Public Management (NPM). (See Hood, 1991, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1995, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1996, 1998; Pollitt and Bouckaert, 2000; Pollitt, 2002</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; Guilfoyle, 2012)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NPM-based practices intensified throughout t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he 1990s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and into the 2000s. In 1994, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Police and Magistrates Cou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rt Act (Home Office, 1994)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> conferred autho</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rity upon the Home Secretary to,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> “…to direct police authorities to es</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tablish levels of performance (‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">performance targets</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) to be aimed at in seeking to ac</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hieve the objective”. (Home Office, 1994, p.16) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This marked a shift toward centralised control through the application of targets, which came to characterise police performance management during subsequent years.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Post 1997</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NPM-orientated performance no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rms were further consolidated through the vigorous application of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> performance indicators, numerical targets, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘league tables’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, audit and inspection, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the holding to account of individuals for perceived ‘poor’ performance. (Loveday, 1998; 2005)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> As part of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1998 Comprehensive Spending Review (CSR), 366 Public Service Agreements (PSAs) were introduced across the public sector, which included over 600 performance targets. (Chief S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ecretary to the Treasury, 1998a,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 1998b; James, 2004)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This was followed by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Police Reform Act of 2002 (Home Office, 2002), which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">heralded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">further </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">intensification of NPM-based practices</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Jones</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, 2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">003</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) The Act:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…provided the Home Secretary with powers to set national police priorities, remove chief office</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rs and directly intervene in the management of local police services”. (Loveday, 2006, p.284)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Interventionist tactics adopted by bodies set up</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to scrutinise forces</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (for example, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Prime Minister’s Delivery Unit (PMDU)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Police Standards Unit (PS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">U)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to assess</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> performance against targets</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and expose ‘poor performers’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> continued throughout the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> first decade of the 21</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Century. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(Hood and Dixon, 2010)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Forces were assessed against criteria set out within the new </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘Policing Performance Assessment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Framework’ (PPAF) (Home Office, 2005),</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which was superseded by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Assessment of Policing and Community Safety</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> framework (APACS), amongst others.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(Home Office, 2007)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8. Following the abolition of APACS in 2010, government policy has moved away from centr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ally-imposed numerical targets, although they are still widely-applied within police forces, as well as by a number of PCCs. Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (HMIC) also retains peer comparison</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> methodology </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">based on a ‘league table’ approa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ch, which ranks forces against each other. Therefore, despite this policy shift at the national level, the legacy of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NPM-orientated</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> practices </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has helped perpetuate a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> dominant mode of performance management that is ingrained within the police psyche.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">9. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is the context within which gaming and other dysfunctional behaviour associated with police mis-recording of crime has occurred.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Police Performance Measurement and Its Prevailing Characteristics</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">10. Effective performance measurement and management sys</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tems are necessary for multiple reasons. Davis (2012) emphasises:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Performance measures are a primary method of ensuring that the police are held accountable in democratic societies”. (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Davis, 2012, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">p.3)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">11. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Evidence of performance is necessary to ensure a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">countability and transparency</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which is vital in fostering policy legit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imacy.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Using the right measures in the right way also helps managers understand how the system is performing, thereby enabling a cycle of continuous improvement. (See Deming, 1986, 1994</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">12. Due to the difficulty in quantifying outcomes in complex public service environments, police performance information has tended</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to focus on quantitative numerical dat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a and is heavily reliant upon proxy measures. This carries significant risks when at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tempting to assess performance, but is further hampered by common practices relating to how the data is routinely presented and used. Coupled with perverse incentives associated with numerical targets and league tables, these practices significantly increa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">se the likelihood of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">gaming, such as in the case of crime being mis-reported. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">13. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In UK policing, there are three dominant components that contribute towards this risk. I refer to them as the ‘three pillars’ of traditional police performance management. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hey are:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Binary comparisons (e.g. comparing current performance data with last month / last quarter / last year etc).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Tabular peer comparisons (e.g. league tables / ranking systems).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Numerical targets.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">14. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Taken in isolation, each has the potential to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">severely distort activity, damaging service delivery and inadvertently encouraging dysfunctional responses. They will now be examined in turn.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Binary Comparisons</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of making binary comparisons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> involves comparing two isolated numeric values, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">then interpreting the difference between them as though it were a trend. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Such c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">omparisons are routinely made with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">last week, last month, last quarter, the average, the cumulative year-to-date figure, and so on. The outcome is that a single numeric value or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> percentage change is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">presente</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d as though it represents a confirmed trajectory within the data.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The following </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">examples</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are typical:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">crime has been reduced by 10% across the force area. This is 3,963 fewer victims of crime compared to the previous 12 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">months...” (North Yorkshire Police, 2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“The number of house burglaries reported to police fell by 36 per cent during Operation Brightshadow, which ran from Monday, October 3 to Sunday, October 9, compared to the week before”. (Essex Police, 2013a)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">17.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">inary comparisons tend to be used because of their si</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mplicity. They appear to convey </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">information about ‘direction of travel’, and make for easy-to-consume quasi-statistical performance information. The danger of using them, however, is that they are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">too</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> si</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mplistic. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bird </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (2005) warn that the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> use encourage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> over-interpretation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of very minor changes amidst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> data, leading to false conclusions. They strongly caution against the practice, noting:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Very particularly the practice of concentrating on a compar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ison with the most recent value, this year’s results compared with last year’s, may be very misleading for reasons including regression to the mean”. (2005, p.14)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">18</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Essentially, the inadequacies associated with binary comparisons make the approach fundam</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">entally incapable of conveying any useful information</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> whatsoever</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Despite this, the practice is probably the single most common method of presenting performance data in UK policing. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The practice also invites</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> unintended behavioural changes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> occur because assumptions about performance based on a binary comparison are often accompanied by implicit exhortations to improve. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A typical example would be where crime appears to have increased, when in fact data presented in a time series may indicate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it is stable. Performance pressures associated with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">such </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an apparently increasing crime rate are one of the factors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> directly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> responsible for mis-recording of crime. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tabular Peer Comparisons (‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">League Tables</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">League tables form part of commonly-used a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">pproaches for assessing comparative performance, yet are vulnerable to methodological instabilities which undermine their efficacy; their use can also lead to unwarranted conclusions being drawn about performance, and act as an unintended catalyst for unhe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">althy internalised competition and dysfunctional responses.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Jacobs and Goddard, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2007</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; Goldstein and Spiegelhalter, 1996; Bird </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 2005)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">20</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e rationale behind </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">their application in policing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is outlined </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as follows:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“The intention is not to ‘set’ one </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">individual force against another nor to use the performance indicators as a proxy for increasing inter-force competition, but rather to broaden the scope of management tools open to senior officers in the context of improving individual force performance”.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (Barton and Beynon</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 2011, p.363)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nevertheless, the probability of gaming (such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">deliberately under-recording crime) is heightened when league tables are used as a tool to compare peers.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hood (2007)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, for example</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> warns:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Like target systems, they are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">likely to produce output distortions as producers learn to find ways that move their organizations up the league tables in ways that do not reflect the intentions of those who framed the rankings, or ignore non-measured activities”. (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2007, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">p.101)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">22.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Behav</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ioural changes are an inevitable consequence of league tables. When they are used in a performance environment alongside the expectation of continual crime reduction, the incentives and pressures integral to the league table approach can influence behaviou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r to the extent that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">de facto</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> purpose for activity becomes to avoid low league table rankings.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">De Maillard and Savage (2012) note:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…the core rationale for police performance tables is more a reflection of a strategy of ‘naming and shaming’ - an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">attempt to drive up performance by identifying the best and worst performing police organisations”. (2012, p.367)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Whilst the intention of policy makers would be that organisations are spurred on by these poor rankings to improve actual performance, the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> evidence points towards widespread gaming and other dysfunctional behaviour being induced as a direct consequence. (See Bevan and Hood, 2006; Hood, 2007; Rothstein 2008)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is suggested that the widespread practice of using league tables in UK police perf</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ormance management is one of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the contributory factors in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of police mis-recording of crime.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Numerical Targets</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The use of numerical targets in police performance management systems is still endemic, and it is my claim that they are the “…single mos</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t pernicious element of conventional management practice…” (Guilfoyle, 2013, p.163) Nevertheless, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">exponents claim </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">numerical </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">argets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> enhance managerial responsibility, motivate workers, and foster public accountability. (Capon </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, 1987; Jennings and Haist, 2004) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">NPM </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reformers and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">proponent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of Goal-Setting Theory </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">laim that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> target</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-driven performance management </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can improve performance,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as well as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">enhance transparency, accountability and legitimacy. (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Locke, 1968; Locke </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, 1981, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1989; Locke and Latham, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2002, 2006; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hoque </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 2004)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A wide range of r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">esearch suggests</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> however,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">target</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">do not</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> improve p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">erformance in complex operating</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> environments. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Moreover,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> some studies indicate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> targets can actually impede performance. (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Kanfer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and Ackerman</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1989) Earley </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (1989) conclude targets do not improve performance for complex tasks. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Similarly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, Horton and Smith (1988) and Mackenzie and Hamilton-Smith (2010) point out complex systems do not respond well to target-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">driven </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">performance ma</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nagement, whilst Loveday (2006)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> argues</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“…public services… are often best described as complex human activity systems; these cannot be managed by crude performance targets”. (2006, p.287) </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Numerical targets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">undermine the effectiveness of police performance management systems </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">because</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> they are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">completely </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">arbitrary</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">neither do they</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> provide a method nor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> capacity for achieving organisational aims. Moreover, they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">act as a trigger for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">behavioural change; indeed,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ir </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">purpose</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is to change behaviour. Bevan and Hood (2006) observe:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Governance by targets rests on the assumption that targets change the behaviour of individuals and organizations…” (2006, p.8)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">28</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">here is a growing body of evidence that indicates many of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the behavioural changes triggered by target-driven performance management are damaging and dysfunctional.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">See Deming, 1986, 1994; Smith, 1990, 1995; Pidd, 2005; Bevan and Hood, 2006; Hood, 2006, 2007; Loveday, 2006, 2008; Rothstein, 2008) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Notably, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Goodha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rt’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s eponymous Law (1975) states:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Any observed statistical regularity will tend to collapse once pressure is placed upon it for control purposes”.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(Goodhart, 1975)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The inference is that in the case of target-driven performance management, pressure to meet targets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">leads to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> counterproductive reactions, leading to statistical and behavioural distortions.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This is precisely what drives police mis-recording of crime; as lo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ng as targets remain for crime reduction, the risk of this type of behaviour remains high. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is because</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“The difficulty with target setting is that despite the good intentions of the target setters, finding a successful strategy to meet targets becomes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e focus of the delivery manager…</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ghobadian </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2009, p.1530)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">30</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, research suggests</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that implicit incentives (i.e.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> rewards and sanctions) typically present within target-driven performance </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> increase the likelihood of unethical </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. For instance, Schweitzer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (2004) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">argue</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">specific goals (i.e. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">numerical targets</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are known to drive improper behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">uch as falsification of records. Bandura (1999) contends</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">erformance goals can caus</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e moral disengagement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> leading to unethical </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">conduct</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, whilst Barsky (2008) explicitly warns:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> “Goal difficulty and specificity are related to unethical behavior, such that exposure to increasingly difficult and specific goals will negatively impact ethical recognition, thereby increasing the likelihood of unethical behavior”.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (2008, p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.70</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">31</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s important to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, however, that ‘everyday’ decisions about whether to record an incident as Offence Type ‘A’ or Offence Type ‘B’ can quite legitimately </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">occur within</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overlap </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">zone’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, where either offence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">classification can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> theoretically </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be correct</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Therefore, whilst the Committee has heard evidence of serious offences </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">allegedly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">being downgraded or mis-recorded, I would posit that much ‘under-reporting’ falls into this ‘technical’ cat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">egory, where there might be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imited direct</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> impact on the public. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> hypothetical</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> example </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ould be the case of a person who is arrested for disorderly behaviour </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in a town centre whilst drunk; t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he non-recordable offence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of Drunk and Disorderly may be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> appropriate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for dealing with the matter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, as might</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a recordable offence under Section 5 of the Public Order Act 1986. The point</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> though, is that where there exists</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> an implicit performance pr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">essure to reduce crime, this can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> introduce an incentive to classify the matt</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">er as D&amp;D rather than Section 5, as the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">former does not count towards crime figures.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This risks distorting the intelligence picture relating to crime patterns, which is a necessary source of information for determining operational responses.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Whether</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> instances </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of mis-recording </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are relatively </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">innocuous, or downright unethical, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">primary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">trigger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> remains</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the same – numerical targets.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Evidence from within policing (and across the public sector) confirms targets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">consistently </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">responsible for generating</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> widespread</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> unintended </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">consequences, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dysfunctional behaviour and collateral damage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Response</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> to the Problem</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Concerns about </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">such adverse consequences h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ave rightly been raised by the Committee, and it is appropriate that steps are taken to prevent reoccurrences. Traditional </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">approaches to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">itigating </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">perverse outcomes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> tend to rely on audit and inspection regimes, sanctions, greater scrutiny, new policies, additional levels of authorisation and the restriction of professional judgment at the frontline. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hood (2006) observes that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> response</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> identified</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> instances of gaming ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> been punitive, prescriptive, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and indicative of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">low trust</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for example, the enactment of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> more rules</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> doctrine.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">35</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> responses, however, are unlike</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ly to prevent the types of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reporting of crime</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> abo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ut which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he Committee has heard evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. This is because the traditional approach of identifying and punishing individuals who have engaged in these behaviours does not address the underlying triggers or latent system conditions that make them likely; ev</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">en predictable. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In considering organisational error, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Reason (2000) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">argues t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hat there are two main approaches to the problem;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">namely, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">person approach</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">systems approach. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This notion is as relevant to understanding institutionalised deviant behaviour as it is in the case of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">simple </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">error. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The dominant tradition of apportioning blame to individuals is indicative of the person approach; conversely, the systems approach suggest</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s that the overriding cause</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of organizational failings </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are rooted firmly in the design of the system </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and the latent conditions prevailing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in it. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Particularly, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Spitzer (2007) contends that the performance management climate of an organisation is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">si</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ngle greatest infl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">uencing factor on culture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Therefore, it is important that the response to the examples outlined in evidence provided </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to the Committee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">addresses</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the fundamental systemic triggers and incentives </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">inadvertently </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">encourage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">police </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mis-recording</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of crime. The evidence pertaining to the last thirty years of p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">olice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> performance management suggests that gaming and dysfunctional behaviour is a widespread and inevitable consequence of performance management systems that ar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e predicated on the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">three pillars</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of binary comparisons, league tables and numerical targets.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is these ingrained practices that must be challenged, rather than merely the symptoms that manifest themselves in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">types of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">behaviour subject to the I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nqui</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ry.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion and Future Direction</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">inally</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, whilst the dysfunctional practices outlined can be traced to these three pillars, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it is not my contention that performance management or measurement is a bad thing. It is absolutely necessary to measure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">performance in order to understand how the system is performing. Evidence of good performance fosters legitimacy and leads to organisational improvement through the sharing of good practice. S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">crutiny of data</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is necessary to aid transparency and accountabil</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ity. Additionally, there is a practical dimension to the collation and analysis of crime data, as it enables managers to interpret trends, understand anomalies and instigate an evidence-based response to confirmed patterns. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The issue, however, is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">how</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this has largely been done in UK policing. The use of binary comparisons, league tables and numerical targets has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">generated</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a legacy of performance management systems which are dominated by characteristics known to make accurate data </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">interpretatio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n impossi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ble</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, as well as</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> drive dysfunctional and even unethical behaviours that work against the system and damage public confidence.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">40</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For this reason, I propose the removal of all numerical targets from police performance frameworks; the only way</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">successfully</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mitigate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> police</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> mis-recording of crime statistics is to remove the incentive for doing so. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is also necessary to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> rethink </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the current use of league tables which attempt to neatly separate forces into ordered rankings, as well as the use of bi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nary comparisons.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">41</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As an alternative, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">endorse the adoption of Systems Thinking principles, and promote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">use of Statistical Process Control </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(SPC) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">charts as a method for unders</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tanding crime data</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> allows for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">much more sophisticated</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> data in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">terpretation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and appreciation of systemic influences and interdependencies,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> should frame performance conversations at all levels.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The removal of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">triggers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> responsible for police mis-recording</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of crime </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">only </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">way to effectively </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">address </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the systemic latent conditions that incentivise the practice.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Replacing the blunt and counterproductive tools of traditional police performance management with SPC-based methodology has the potential to signal a paradigmatic shift that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> significantly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">limit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> gaming and dysfunctional behaviour, whilst signalling more mature and insightful performance management norms.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">References </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Barton, H. and Beynon, N. (2011) ‘Targeted Criteria Performance Improvement – An Investigation of a ‘Most Similar’ UK Police Force’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">International Journal of Public Sector Management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. 24 (4): 356-367</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bandura, A. (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1999</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ‘Moral Disengagement in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Perpetration of Inhumanities’.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Personality and Social Psychology Review. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: 193 - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">209</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">